  "background": "An important historical case-control study completed by Doll and Hill found that 647 of the 649 lung cancer cases were smokers. In contrast, 622 of 649 controls smoked.",
  "task": [
    {
      "query": "Display these data as a 2-by-2 table.",
      "answer": "\\begin{tabular}{r|r|r|r}\\hline Smoke & Cases & Non-cases & Total\\\\\\cline{1-4}+ & 647 & 622 & 1269\\\\\\cline{1-4}- & 2 & 27 & 29\\\\\\cline{1-4}Total & 649 & 649 & 1298\\\\\\hline\\end{tabular}"
    },
    {
      "query": "Calculate the odds ratio (OR) associated with smoking.",
      "answer": "$$\\widehat{OR} = \\frac{647 \\cdot 27}{622 \\cdot 2} = 14.04$$ This suggests that the smokers had 14 times the risk of nonsmokers."
    },
    {
      "query": "Include a 95% confidence interval for the OR.",
      "answer": "Determining the confidence interval for the $OR$: $$\\ln(14.04) = 2.6419$$ $$SE = \\sqrt{647^{-1} + 622^{-1} + 2^{-1} + 27^{-1}} = 0.7350$$ The $95\\% \\mathrm{CI}$ for $\\mathrm{OR} = e^{(2.6419 \\pm 1.96 \\times 0.7350)} = e^{(1.2013, 4.0825)} = 3.3$ to $59.3$."
    }
